				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">1MΩ+47pF seems ridiculous, but if it's reliable, then sure, whatever: the 4013 is a CMOS part so has approximately no input current.<br /><br />In the Famicom, M2 and /RD4016 are combined to produce a signal that should be<br />* Driven high during not-M2 of a cycle when reading from $4016<br />* Driven low during M2 of a cycle when reading from $4016<br />* External weak pullup the rest of the time.<br /><br />In the NES, it tentatively looks like /RD4016 just goes directly to the controller jack instead.<br /><br />Tangent: this should mean that the DPCM controller glitch should cause only one bit deletion on NES decks, but multiple bit deletions on original HVC-001 Famicoms.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
						<tr valign="middle">
							<td class="gensmall" align="right">
							
							</td>
						</tr>
						</table>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		</tr>

